OK, so he restaged events; he "lied to tell the truth" but beyond that he 
stirred up a flurry of emotions through juxtaposition of image and sound. He 
coyly manipulated his case -- editorializing rather than documenting. It's 
symbiotic; he's driven home not only these events of Flint, Mich., but his 
subtext as well. If we are to be told a story with blinders on, then that story 
should be called fiction. 
