<HEADLINE>
<P>
WALL STREET / JOHN CRUDELE: DREXEL WAS NO SURPRISE BUT MARKET'S CALM WAS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN CRUDELE, JOHN CRUDELE is a financial columnist for the New York Post. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
What was the biggest surprise last week? To many on Wall Street, it wasn't that 
Drexel Burnham Lambert was forced into bankruptcy. That was expected. 
</P>
<P>
More surprising was that the financial markets reacted as calmly as they did as 
Drexel was going out of business. 
</P>
<P>
"I'm amazed at how the Drexel event was absorbed without a ripple," says Donald 
Straszheim, chief economist for Merrill Lynch Capital Markets Group. "It does 
seem that somebody in Washington has done a good bid of homework since 1987 to 
handle special events." 
</P>
<P>
The fact that the stock and bond markets barely shrugged this past Monday, 
Tuesday and Wednesday as Drexel was self-destructing brought out the conspiracy 
theories. These are the same theories that surfaced Oct. 16, the first trading 
day after the Oct. 13 mini-crash. And the theories are similar to those 
expressed by many after the crash of October, 1987, when people speculated that 
somehow the government intervened to stabilize stock prices. 
</P>
<P>
The government has always denied that it would interfere in the stock market, 
and nothing can prove that to the contrary. But that didn't stop some market 
pros last week from suspecting that the subtle hand of Washington was again at 
work. 
</P>
<P>
In Chicago, for instance, the stock index futures markets were buzzing with 
rumors that Washington was putting pressure on big trading houses to give the 
market a lift. 
</P>
<P>
"I heard those rumors," says one futures trader. "I don't think the government 
is pressuring people to buy. Maybe there is a certain amount of jawboning and 
encouragement not to force the market down." 
</P>
<P>
There could, of course, be another explanation for the nonchalance. Drexel has 
been in trouble for a long time, and the markets may have already made price 
adjustments in case of its demise. 
</P>
<P>
"The (bankruptcy) filing was largely anticipated by the market," says James 
Rosenfeld, finance professor at Emory University. "Everybody was aware of the 
financial woes." In fact, Rosenfeld feels that the markets may have skipped 
right over the bad news and started looking at the bright side. 
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve may have to reduce interest rates to keep other Wall Street 
firms solvent, says Rosenfeld. 
</P>
<P>
But keep the Drexel situation in perspective. 
</P>
<P>
Interest rates are all that the financial markets really care about. If the 
Drexel bankruptcy had affected borrowing costs, then it would have been of 
major importance to the stock market. 
</P>
<P>
In the weeks ahead -- when Drexel is long forgotten -- Wall Street will still 
be concerned about rising foreign interest rates and this nation's sluggish 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
And unless there is a sudden improvement in rates there or the economy here, 
the stock market will still be on shaky ground. 
</P>
<P>
Where are interest rates going? John Paulus, Morgan Stanley &amp; Co.'s chief 
economist, said last week that he thinks they'll climb. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Coniston Bid for UAL May Depend on Arbs 
</P>
<P>
Are Coniston Partners' chances of beating UAL Corp.'s board in a proxy battle 
slipping away? 
</P>
<P>
Coniston and UAL would agree that the number of shares of the airline company 
in the hands of arbitragers, or speculators, has fallen dramatically in the 
past few months. Arbs, of course, are the natural allies of Coniston in any 
proxy fight. 
</P>
<P>
Coniston and UAL try to keep track of the holdings of arbs through informal 
surveys. Last week, UAL's proxy solicitation firm, Kissel-Blake Inc., quietly 
called arbs and, I'm told, estimated that these speculators hold about 6 
million of UAL's 22 million outstanding shares. At the peak, they were believed 
to have owned 9.5 million to 10 million. But the sharp plunge in UAL's stock in 
recent months has caused many to liquidate. 
</P>
<P>
Coniston Partners, which has been threatening a proxy fight since last year, 
owns 2.6 million UAL shares. That means that if Coniston decides to go forward 
with a proxy contest -- or its close cousin, a consent solicitation -- it would 
have to win the vote of approximately 2.5 million shares to achieve a majority. 
</P>
<P>
While it is still very likely that Coniston will win, any further reduction in 
the number of shares held by arbs won't make the effort any easier. It could be 
especially difficult to oust the board if Coniston can't come up with an 
alternative that UAL shareholders find more attractive than whatever the 
company's board ends up proposing. 
</P>
<P>
Coniston was to have begun a consent solicitation in January, but it backed off 
from that threat when it looked as though UAL was making progress in its 
efforts for a buyout led by management and the airline's unions. 
</P>
<P>
It is now February, and UAL is still trying to structure some sort of buyout or 
restructuring. A couple of times each week, Coniston, the unions representing 
UAL employees and the company's management get together at the New York offices 
of First Boston Corp., the investment banking firm, to discuss the situation. 
While these meeting are supposed to be secret, Wall Street keeps very close 
tabs of when they occur. The only thing that Wall Street doesn't know is the 
amount of progress being made behind closed doors. 
</P>
<P>
Coniston is said to be happy with the progress of the talks. That's why there 
hasn't been much gossip lately about a proxy battle. But if Coniston should 
become dissatisfied at some point, it is going to wish it had more help from 
arbs. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Long-Distance Carriers Not Much Different 
</P>
<P>
You've seen the commercials: A guy on a pay phone tries to call Phoenix and 
accidentally gets Fiji. He becomes so frustrated that he vows to go back to the 
good service of AT&amp;T. 
</P>
<P>
MCI Communications makes similar claims for the quality of its long-distance 
telephone service. So does US Sprint. 
</P>
<P>
Which service is really the best? Smith Barney, Harris Upham recently surveyed 
managers of corporate telephone systems and found that there really isn't much 
difference in quality. 
</P>
<P>
Smith Barney says it sent out 110 questionnaires in its second annual survey. 
Of the 52 people who returned them, 48 said they managed annual budgets of $1 
million or more. 
</P>
<P>
The managers were asked to rate the long-distance carriers on a scale of 1 to 5 
(with 5 being best) in network quality, service and sales. In quality, AT&amp;T 
got a 4.2 rating, Sprint 3.9. and MCI 3.5. AT&amp;T also led in service with a 
3.6 rating, followed by Sprint and MCI tied at 3.3. In sales, Sprint led with 
3.4, AT&amp;T was second at 3.2 and MCI third with 3.1. 
</P>
<P>
Overall, AT&amp;T's rating was 4.2, Sprint's 3.9 and MCI's 3.5. 
</P>
<P>
Analyst Charles Schelke, who conducted the poll, concluded that the 
long-distance phone companies were "generally comparable." He told clients in a 
report called TeleTrends that "while all carriers now appear to be providing 
satisfactory service, no one is consistently providing exceptional service." 
</P>
<P>
Incidentally, AT&amp;T did moderately better in this survey than in a similar 
poll Smith Barney conducted a year earlier. MCI did a tiny bit better, and 
Sprint's rate was unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Beware Greenspan's Soothing Forecasts 
</P>
<P>
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan pulled off a magic trick a few weeks 
ago when he calmed a jittery stock market and pacified Congress by saying the 
chances of an economic recession have been reduced. But just how good a 
forecaster has Greenspan been? 
</P>
<P>
Take a look at his predictions in 1981, the last time that the nation's economy 
slipped into a recession, and you'll see that sometimes his crystal ball gets a 
little foggy. 
</P>
<P>
In April, 1981, Greenspan -- then a private economist but also an unofficial 
adviser to President Reagan -- predicted that the U.S.' gross national product 
would grow 0.7% in the third quarter. But by August, Greenspan had dramatically 
changed his opinion -- predicting, instead, that GNP would decline 1.1%. 
</P>
<P>
The change came after a government report in July said business conditions were 
weakening. According to the Commerce Department, the GNP actually grew by 1.8% 
in third quarter 1981. 
</P>
<P>
Greenspan further predicted that April that GNP would grow 3.6% in the fourth 
quarter. But by August he was predicting a decline of 0.2%. The economy 
actually declined 5.5% that quarter. 
</P>
<P>
Also in that month, Greenspan predicted that the U.S. economy would grow by 
3.8% in the first quarter of 1982. He changed that estimate in August to an 
increase of just 0.8%. GNP actually declined 5.9%. 
</P>
<P>
Two successive quarters of contraction -- as happened in the fourth quarter of 
1981 and the first quarter of 1982 -- are popularly defined as a recession. 
Greenspan had correctly predicted an economic downturn (albeit a slight one), 
but it did take two tries and a little hint from the government before he got 
it right. 
</P>
<P>
Greenspan's prediction of a rebound in the first quarter of 1982, of course, 
was way off target. 
</P>
<P>
His record got a little better in the second quarter of 1982. Greenspan's 
revised estimate of a 3.5% gain in the second quarter of 1982 wasn't too far 
off the actual 1.2% growth experienced in that period. But Greenspan went back 
to his losing ways with his long-range prediction for the third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
Greenspan's revised forecast in August, 1981, was for 4.3% growth in the third 
quarter of 1982. The economy actually declined 3.2% that quarter. 
</P>
<P>
In short, the closest Greenspan had come to spotting a recession was his 
prediction of a decline in GNP in the third and fourth quarters of 1981. But he 
was forecasting a short, painless downturn. The recession actually lasted, 
according to the Commerce Department, from July, 1981, to November, 1982. And 
it was anything but painless. 
</P>
<P>
Greenspan, one hopes, has a better feel for the economy now that he has access 
to all those government statistics. But the financial markets should also 
remember that a Fed chairman can't always be as candid as he'd like to be -- 
especially if he is trying to calm a jittery nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
