<HEADLINE>
<P>
ERMA BOMBECK: SIGNS SAY GOD IS NOT A VEGETARIAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ERMA BOMBECK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Food shoppers are being faced with a major decision these days. Should they buy 
a zucchini or make the house payment? It's happened before. Every time the 
South experiences a deep freeze, the price of fruits and vegetables soars out 
of reach. 
</P>
<P>
To the veggie freaks whose idea of pigging out is to graze on the front lawn, 
these are indeed dark days. For me, it's an omen. 
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago I said, "God, if you want me to get off this crummy diet, give me 
a sign." The very next day in the supermarket I picked up a single tomato. It 
was marked $3. At that very moment, I heard organ music. The tomato was 
returned and I hit the Dove bars. 
</P>
<P>
It doesn't take much to dissuade me from buying and eating greens. Not only am 
I not a vegetable disciple, I have never been convinced that vegetables make 
you thin. The first time my mom took me to the zoo, I watched as the keeper 
threw a bucket of greens to an orangutan. I wasn't the brightest kid on the 
block, but I figured here was an animal that exercised regularly, ate healthy 
and got a lot of sleep, and look how he turned out. He had a waistline the size 
of a Disney parking lot. 
</P>
<P>
That sorta set the pace for me. I'm possibly the only person who can visit a 
salad bar and run up a calorie tab of 1,200 on one plate. I start with a bed of 
croutons and drown them in a sea of blue cheese with bacon bits, then garnish 
it with two cherry tomatoes. 
</P>
<P>
As is generally the case, carbohydrate eaters are attracted to mates who thrive 
on proteins. I came from a family where gravy was a beverage and ketchup was a 
vegetable. My husband's family bought lettuce by the field. 
</P>
<P>
After we married, it wasn't easy trying to blend our eating habits. I thought a 
long time before I made a decision to bring a child into a world polluted by 
Brussels sprouts. 
</P>
<P>
When my husband looked into the refrigerator last week, he said, "Where's the 
vegetables?" 
</P>
<P>
I handed him an artichoke with the price on it and he gasped. "Let me guess. 
You bought a designer artichoke? I thought I told you to get eggplant." 
</P>
<P>
"If you want me to buy eggplant," I said, "I'll arrange financing, but the way 
I look at it, we are being given a sign that the world is coming to an end as 
we know it." 
</P>
<P>
"What kind of nonsense is that?" he asked. 
</P>
<P>
"All the foods that experts say are good for you are dwindling -- fresh fish, 
vegetables, fruits." 
</P>
<P>
"The shortage can be explained," he said. "The weather is an act of God." 
</P>
<P>
"That's what I've been telling you," I said. "Hear the organ?" 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
