381 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
'MUD DUCKS' WIN ROUND IN FIGHT FOR ANCHORAGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By NANCY RAY, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A San Diego appeals court on Friday threw out the convictions of nine boat 
owners found guilty of anchoring illegally in San Diego Bay -- a victory for 
the Mud Ducks of Emory Bay. 
</P>
<P>
The motley collection of houseboats has been anchored in the snug harbor -- 
within sight of the affluent Coronado Cays residential marina -- for years, 
long before the San Diego Unified Port District rescinded the right to free 
anchorage anywhere in the bay. 
</P>
<P>
The action by a Superior Court appeals panel was based on the failure of a 
South Bay municipal judge to allow the boaters to videotape testimony of an 
expert witness for presentation at their trial a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
Joyce Graf, one of the live-aboards who is fighting the Port District to retain 
free anchorage in Emory Cove, said the boaters "are flying high" after the 
victory, which she conceded may be short-lived. 
</P>
<P>
Deputy Dist. Atty. Jennifer Yackle asked the panel for a written copy of its 
decision in anticipation of an appeal. 
</P>
<P>
The Emory Cove contingent, many of whom have called the Silver Strand anchorage 
home for more than a decade, are fighting Port District attempts to move them 
from the protected cove to an unsheltered anchorage in mid-bay. 
</P>
<P>
The only legal anchorage designated by the Port District in the southern half 
of San Diego Bay lies off the mouth of the Sweetwater River, next to a ship 
lane used by commercial and Navy vessels. Emory Cove residents say that the 
open waters and wash from passing ships would wreck their aging houseboats if 
they were forced to move there. 
</P>
<P>
Port District commissioners passed an ordinance restricting anchorage in the 
southern part of the bay in l987 and issued eviction orders to the live-aboards 
and other craft in the southern bay. 
</P>
<P>
Leo Shaw, attorney for a majority of the Emory Cove contingent, said that the 
group also is fighting a Port District effort to dredge a parking lot used by 
the Emory Cove boaters in an effort to force them to move and is challenging 
the legality of the Port District ordinance regulating anchorage areas and 
speed limits in the bay. 
</P>
<P>
Shaw praised Graf and her husband, Lawrence, who live aboard a converted 
minesweeper anchored in Emory Cove, as "the only ones who have had the guts to 
challenge the Port District" on the new bay regulations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Martin Eichman shows part of the crack that runs through several rooms 
of his home in Oceanside. DAVE GATLEY / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
