<HEADLINE>
<P>
LAWYER ADMITS GUILT IN ELABORATE FRAUD PLOT; 
</P>
<P>
INSURANCE SCAM: EXPERTS SAY THE CASE IS EMERGING AS ONE OF THE LARGEST CRIMINAL 
PROSECUTIONS OF ATTORNEYS IN U.S. HISTORY. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MYRON LEVIN, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Woodland Hills attorney who wanted to be a judge instead went before one in 
San Diego on Friday to admit criminal involvement in an elaborate insurance 
fraud by a group of Los Angeles-area lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
Bruce Ficht, 39, pleaded guilty to a single count of mail fraud, becoming the 
fourth attorney convicted in a case experts say is emerging as one of the 
largest criminal prosecutions of attorneys in U.S. history. 
</P>
<P>
The four lawyers and two other people convicted thus far all lived or worked in 
the San Fernando Valley. Prosecutors have said 10 or 15 more attorneys could be 
indicted in the case, which has targeted a ring of lawyers whom prosecutors 
have called the "Alliance". 
</P>
<P>
No sentencing date was set for Ficht on the mail fraud count, which carries a 
maximum penalty of five years' imprisonment and a $250,000 fine. Although 
Ficht's plea bargain was sealed by U.S. District Judge Judith N. Keep, the 
agreement is believed to require Ficht to surrender his license to practice 
law. 
</P>
<P>
Ficht declined comment after his brief court appearance, and Assistant U.S. 
Atty. George D. Hardy would not discuss specifics of Ficht's plea. But Hardy 
said that "with all of these cases we've required that the attorneys surrender 
their licenses." 
</P>
<P>
In an interview with The Times more than a year ago, Ficht denied any 
wrongdoing and bristled at allegations of misconduct. "Between you and I, I 
have hopes one day of running for judge," he said. 
</P>
<P>
But, on Friday, barely speaking above a whisper in response to questions from 
Keep, Ficht admitted conspiring with other lawyers to manipulate litigation and 
bilk insurance carriers. "In furtherance of that scheme, I assisted in billing 
insurance carriers and assisted other attorneys in billing insurance carriers," 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
Ficht and those previously convicted described a sort of legal franchise 
operation, in which senior members of the ring set up new members with their 
own law offices, creating additional billing centers for the group. The new 
members were loaned start-up funds and sent insured defendants, and in return 
agreed to pay the group a percentage of their insurance company billings. 
</P>
<P>
Ficht told Keep he struck such a bargain with Marc Kent, a former Studio City 
lawyer who has become a key government witness since pleading guilty last 
October. Kent helped Ficht set up his law office in November, 1986, and sent 
him clients in three complex litigations in which others in the group were 
involved, known as the Amgo, Syndico and Mint Financial cases. 
</P>
<P>
Ficht said he took advice and direction from Kent, even though his Syndico 
client and Kent's had adverse interests. 
</P>
<P>
Richard A. Banks, who pleaded guilty last month, and Alan M. Hersh, who pleaded 
guilty in December, also said they were recruited by Kent. 
</P>
<P>
Kent, in turn, said Lynn B. Stites, whom authorities called the mastermind of 
the scheme, recruited him in about 1984. Stites, who has not been charged, has 
refused requests for interviews. 
</P>
<P>
The lawyers appeared together in a number of complex civil cases in San Diego, 
Los Angeles and Orange that usually involved claims of investment fraud. These 
were a special type of case in which insurance companies had to pay legal bills 
but lost the right to pick their policyholders' lawyers or direct defense 
strategy. 
</P>
<P>
Once in a case together, the lawyers allegedly used exhaustive discovery to run 
up defense bills, and filed cross-claims, or secondary lawsuits, against one 
another's clients, increasing each attorney's workload and defense bills. 
</P>
<P>
Although it did not figure in Ficht's plea Friday, Wayne Watson, a businessman 
who was sued in the Amgo case in San Diego and secretly worked with federal 
investigators said that Ficht once offered to pay him $300 a month to drop his 
Amgo attorney and retain Ficht to conduct his insurance-paid defense. Other 
defendants in the case were receiving payments from their attorneys, Watson 
said. 
</P>
<P>
"It just slapped me upside the face as to being very blatant . . . what they 
were doing here," Watson said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
Ficht, who denied Watson's account of the conversation in a 1988 interview, 
ended up with another Amgo defendant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA021890-0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 178152 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
February 18, 1990, Sunday, Bulldog Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 1; Column 2; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
833 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMENTARY; 
</P>
<P>
LET'S FACE IT: NEITHER SIDE CARES ABOUT THE FANS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BILL REYNOLDS, PROVIDENCE JOURNAL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
So here we go again. 
</P>
<P>
The Great American Lockout looms on the horizon like some thunder cloud at a 
Fourth of July picnic, and once again professional sports is faced with the 
specter of a work stoppage. Five years ago, it was major-league baseball. Three 
years ago, it was the National Football League. Now it's baseball again. 
</P>
<P>
Once again, sports have become just another labor-management feud, no different 
than the police and fire department unions haggling over a new contract. Forget 
knowing the infield-fly rule. To really understand baseball now, you now have 
to be familiar with the life and times of Samuel Gompers. 
</P>
<P>
And once again, we sports fans are supposed to know whom to root for. 
</P>
<P>
Are the players at fault, these spoiled millionaires who think it's their 
birthright to never have to work again once their careers are over? Or is it 
the owners, those bastions of business who have created these Monopoly-money 
contracts in the first place? 
</P>
<P>
Sometimes it seems like you need some advanced degree in negotiations to 
decipher all this. But one thing is as clear as the padlocks on the gates of 
spring-training sites. 
</P>
<P>
Neither side cares about the fans. 
</P>
<P>
Think about it. No one is talking about reducing ticket prices. No one is 
talking about reducing the cost of a hot dog. No one is saying anything about 
reducing the price of parking. Neither side is talking about putting pressure 
on cable companies to reduce their prices, or lobbying to put more games on 
regular television instead of pay television. 
</P>
<P>
All of these things would help the fan. They would help stem the tide of people 
almost needing second jobs to afford season tickets. Of having to buy sports 
channels on cable television if you want to watch many of the games. Of the 
always-rising cost of what it takes to be a sports fan nowadays. 
</P>
<P>
Instead, we get talk of minimum salaries, revenue sharing, free agency and the 
amount of time a player needs to be eligible for free agency. We get talk of 
collusion and pay-for-performance, talk that makes your eyes glaze over. 
</P>
<P>
And they want you and me to care who wins this so-called labor struggle? 
</P>
<P>
Please. Be serious. 
</P>
<P>
The modern sports climate is all about greed. How much and how often. Who gets 
the biggest piece of a pie that keeps getting bigger and bigger. It's about 
owners who keep putting more and more games on pay television, all the while 
continuing to see their franchises escalate in value. It's about players who 
charge little kids for autographs at card shows, and then give us nonsense 
about how it's a great way to meet all their fans. 
</P>
<P>
Why is this allowed to go on? 
</P>
<P>
Simple. 
</P>
<P>
We let it go on. You, and I, and anyone else who are baseball fans. We buy 
sports channels on cable television. We buy tickets to the games, regardless of 
the prices. 
</P>
<P>
We are perceived as a captive audience, one that will be there regardless of 
what side emerges as the winner in this so-called labor struggle. We are the 
great unwashed, and we are treated as such. 
</P>
<P>
Maybe that's because we want baseball to be some throwback to innocence, some 
childhood time when players are loyal to the teams they play for, to the fans 
who cheer them, some gone-forever time when no one knew what most players made, 
and few cared. We want the players to care as much as we do. 
</P>
<P>
We don't like it when players imply that their families and their personal 
futures come before their allegiance to the team they play for and the fans who 
cheer them. All that speaks of real life, one of the things we go to baseball 
games to forget about. 
</P>
<P>
That's the problem with the lockout. 
</P>
<P>
It takes away all the pretense, robs us of the innocence. It clearly 
demonstrates major-league baseball is a business, no different from any other, 
complete with its omnipresent labor problems. 
</P>
<P>
Say it ain't so, Joe. 
</P>
<P>
Not that we won't be back when the lockout is over. 
</P>
<P>
We will come crawling back like some jilted lover who gets a second chance, our 
hearts once again on our sleeve. 
</P>
<P>
For we are all junkies and, like junkies everywhere, we will get our fix, 
whatever the cost. We are the suckers who will stand in line to pay players for 
autographs at card shows. We will pay at least $10 to park, and then pay more 
for soggy hotdogs and watered-down beer. We will keep paying for sports 
channels on TV, and stay up late at night to watch the World Series because 
some TV mogul somewhere figured out that ratings are better. 
</P>
<P>
That is a reality. 
</P>
<P>
But don't insult me. 
</P>
<P>
Spare me any talk about who is right and who is wrong, in this Great American 
Lockout. Both sides are portraits in greed. The owners who cry poverty while 
their franchises continue to escalate in value. The players who want us to 
think they are some poor struggling union in the middle of a battle with big, 
bad management. 
</P>
<P>
So spare me any talk that this latest work stoppage is any marvelous quest. 
This is about what professional sports have become, and there are no winners. 
</P>
<P>
Just people like you and me that neither side cares about. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, A padlock holds shut the gates to players' parking area at Mets Stadium 
in Port St. Lucie, Fla., symbolizing baseball owners' lockout of the players 
from spring training. United Press International 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
